# React Hooks Rules

## When to Use Hooks

| Situation | Need hooks? |
|-----------|-------------|
| Static page (text, images, no clicks) | No |
| Button click, modal, form input | Yes — `useState` |
| Load data from API | Yes — `useState` + `useEffect` |
| Share data across components | Yes — `useContext` or store |

## Data Fetching Pattern

Always include `loading` and `error` state:

```javascript
const [data, setData] = useState([]);
const [loading, setLoading] = useState(true);
const [error, setError] = useState(null);

useEffect(() => {
  fetch("/api/services")
    .then((res) => res.json())
    .then((result) => { setData(result); setLoading(false); })
    .catch((err) => { setError("Failed to load"); setLoading(false); });
}, []);

if (loading) return <p>Loading...</p>;
if (error) return <p>{error}</p>;
return <div>{/* show data */}</div>;
```

## Custom Hooks

- Name starts with `use` (e.g. `useToggle`, `useFetch`)
- One hook = one purpose
- Place in `src/hooks/`
- Return `[state, setter]` for simple state, `{data, loading}` for data

```javascript
// hooks/useToggle.js
export function useToggle(initial = false) {
  const [value, setValue] = useState(initial);
  const toggle = useCallback(() => setValue(v => !v), []);
  return [value, toggle];
}
```

## Rules

- Hooks only inside component function, at top level
- `useState` at top for things that change (open/close, form values)
- `useEffect` for fetch or run-on-load logic
- Static pages: no hooks needed
